segments.text: Let me test this.
Testing.
OK, we can continue.
Consequently, you felt that the quality of the students and of the instructors is very high.
Did you go to a certain class?
for a week and then go to another class for a week?
Or did you go daily?
What was their routine?
The best of my memory, and I still think they follow the same system, they had us broken up in groups.
And we'd have what's called seminars, which study, for instance, for maybe the first month,
Well, the whole outfit first, the entire class, and I think I remember about 300 people, maybe, that worked on it.
It must have been at least 300.
The first part of the, it was supposed to last a year, by the way.
Yeah, and it lasted seven months.
Right.
And why?
The Korean War broke out.
Yeah.
So it was a short course.
And we didn't get, I was the one class that we didn't get to finish.
So they had to break it off short.
But needless to say, by that time, I was glad to get out of the Air Force.
I had it under my belt and on my record anyhow, so I was glad to go.
But they had you in seminars for a while, and then you go to a .
Especially like economics, strategy, some history, military history.
Then as we got towards the end of the course, each seminar became more specific and a lot of times about, let's say, shorter.
Like we'd study fighter tactics for tactical air warfare.
Just ground air support, that type of thing.
And we'd have a monitor.
And we'd break the classes down into panels then.
Maybe 15, 20 officers.
And the instructors, or if you will, the monitors, what do we call them?
I guess monitors.
Officer types, you know, a couple of us, colonel, lieutenant colonel, lieutenant.
They'd monitor the panels and moderators.
And we'd actually sit around the table and discuss and argue amongst ourselves.
The main ones that I can remember and old Charlie Bond became famous for was when we got on international stuff and the Russians.
Because, you see, I've been over in Russia a year.
I had very definite opinions and didn't hold back in expressing what I felt very strong about.
And I was complimentary towards the Russians in a lot of ways about the capabilities of what I saw.
And I became known as Red or Pink Charlie.
But I was respected.
We graded each other.
Students graded each other at times.
And I was very proud of what my classmates thought of me.
Why'd they call you Pink Charlie?
Because you had a couple of good things to say about the Soviet Union?
Yeah, and of course this was a period of McCarthyism and anti-communist fear.
And I didn't also, at that time, I think I told you before, I was still fairly well convinced that the war had been inevitable between us.
And I always opened my
comments, and I still say it.
You've heard me say it to you.
I've been, I've dealt with practically every national portion of the world, been on practically every continent in the world, except Korea, and I've met people all over the world.
Far East, Europe, India, your name is Africa, South America.
I've never met a man on the street I'm talking
man of the street type I'm talking about, civilian versus civilian.
And fighter pilot versus fighter pilot, professionally speaking.
I've never met a race of people more like the Americans than the Russians.
Now, that's the people of the street I'm talking about.
Now, war erupts in June of 1941 by August of 1951.
Did I say 41?
I thought 51.
By August of 1951,
You're no longer a student.
Were you eager to get to that war?
Yes, but I didn't go to that war.
I know you didn't, but were you eager?
Oh, yeah.
Did you want to become a combat fighter pilot?
As a matter of fact, I was picked at one time and knew I was going to be assigned to command one of the two tactical ground control groups that was in the Iron Tire Force.
There were two of them.
This is a ground control environment, if you will, including radars and all the communication equipment for controlling tactical air warfare and giving close air support to the Army.
We had two of them in the United States, in the United States Air Force.
And one of them obviously had to go to Korea because we were in the war.
And I was picked and tapped, and I was going to go command that unit.
How did you feel about that?
And I was tickled to death.
Of course, I...
I would prefer it to have been in one of the fighter outfits.
And I admit I had a little qualms about, gee, what's this going to do to my future, and so forth and so on.
But at least I knew I was going to be in the war.
And then the next thing I knew, when the assignments came out, I was ordered to go to Northeast Air Command to do air defense planning for

the northern area of uh well the northern area of the western hemisphere namely tuli the huge base of tuli and continue the implementation of the plans that i had originally laid on for continuing the air defense pine tree system of radars up the coast of uh of canada in other words i was picked
to implement the plan that I had laid down as a planner the previous year.
Is that why they sent you to Newfoundland?
I was more qualified, much more qualified to do it because I had drawn up the plans for it.
How could I argue that?
True, but what were your feelings when you found out that you weren't going to Korea, you were going to Newfoundland?
I'd make the feelings, but at the same time, I knew this time I was going to have a family with me.
That helped offset the feelings.
And I rapidly gave up any hard feelings about losing the opportunity to go to war because I wasn't completely sold on commanding this ground environment control outfit.
I'd have been on the ground too much, and it didn't particularly grab me.
So I was glad.
And it gave me more confidence.
It was a challenging job in the treated zones of the polar area of the world, and something I had not really been experienced in.
Here was something else I was going to get some experience in.
And you were there from August 1951 to May of 1954, and you eventually became the commander of the 64th Air Division.
See, that's what the plan was laid out.
You were a full colonel at this time.
Tell me about your command.
What was under your command?
First, I was the director of air defense from 1951 to 1952.
There again, to finish the planning, detailed planning.
if you will, take field trips and supervise the installation of radar sites and all, which is extremely interesting, flying up and down Labrador Coast in amphibious type airplanes.
Then going up to the frigid north with Thule Air Base and planning the, now that was a new planning completely, down the planning for the... And you were working right with the Canadians.
Well, in Greenland, I had to be working with Denmark.
Being there again was international planning.
And I, again, was doing international planning with another nation.
And really what we had to do was get their approval, that's all I had to do.
It was more of a political and diplomatic thing.
But this was the engineering feats and installing equipment on the ice cap on the periphery of Tule Air Force Base for our defense program.
That's exactly what it is, Tule.
That flag right there.
It's north of the Arctic Circle.
Oh, yeah.
And there's the North Pole.
These are weather sites.
Floating ice on this one.
It's on the north.
It's on the northern, western edge of Greenland.
It's like it's pretty close.
Really north of Greenland.
Everything's north of there.
the North Pole.
I have been within 50 miles of the North Pole.
Key three of weather stations on a floating ice.
It may still be up there as far as I know.
But I'm probably manned by civilians now.
What were the problems there?
Were they mostly technical?
Mostly logistical.
In frigid conditions, building

For instance, a huge hangar that housed a B-52 on a tundra that was frozen correctly all the year, and then when it would melt, it would melt so far down on the ground, it would melt too far down and ruin the foundation of the building.
The engineering feats that were accomplished up there were just something out of this world.
What were some of them?
But the cost.
Well, for instance, the barracks and operations building and maintenance building all had to be built above the ground, let's say, primarily on six-by-six type logs to give about three feet clearance
under the floor of the building and the ground so that the heat from the building and the floor would not melt the ground underneath it and then ruin the foundation of the building.
And also let the flowing snow go past the building, underneath it, or above it, or beside of it, and not stack up and use this and practically cover it up.
And actually cover it up.
I've seen 20, 40-foot buildings completely covered up with snow along the Labrador coast.
All the radars had to have radons on them to protect them from wind as high as 140 knots.
Well, they went in 140 knots, but we lost several over Labrador, California.
And it took the radar with them.
Did you lose any men?
No.
As a matter of fact, we, it was all, well, the Canadians helped us plan all this stuff.
And of course, by the time we got to the plans for, you know, complete all those plans,
plan for the radar sites up in northern Greenland.
It's still frigid north, so it was applicable then, except on the ice cap, how to construct the basic buildings and things on the ice cap.
And that's where we took some special engineering studies.
The Corps of Engineers did all of this.
But boy, there was some expert consultants, as a matter of fact, from other countries, brought in from the
Norway and Sweden and Iceland, construction companies that were familiar with the North, would come over.
What we'd do, for instance, put the radar on the ice cap north of what we call number one radar site.
We had two radars on the ice cap about 15, 20 miles north and east of the base proper.

dug out a big trench, huge trench, into the ice cap proper, then sunk about an 18-foot diameter conduit type, typical culvert you've seen, sunk that in the ice cap, and then covered it over, and then built with inside that iron pipe, if you will, everything we want to build, and then just stuck a hole up to it with a radar antenna sticking above the ice cap with a radar moment.
That's the way that was.
every inch of the water for the main site.
Would you lose any of those?
No.
It would melt?
No.
It would melt.
The way they built that idea, it couldn't melt, but it was looted.
The main radar site, what's called a direction center south of the base, was really on a base proper, and it was just off the edge of the ice cap, but up on what we call a P-mount, a high peak.

We had to build a road up to it, and we had to haul water up to it, and we'd haul water up to it during the summertime where we'd fill up a huge storage tank inside of a building which you had to keep heated to keep from freezing in the wintertime.
And of course we had to haul fuel up there.
It was completely a different logistical concept.
Very, very interesting.
Now you were the commander up there in the 64th Air Division, and how large was that?
How many people did you have under your command?
Well, we had a fighter squadron at Goose Air Base, a fighter squadron at Harmon Air Force Base, and we had a little detachment of three aircraft up at Thule.
That was the fighters, and radar sites we had about
One, two, three, four, five, six, about ten radar sites up the Canadian coast and on Newfoundland proper and then on Greenland around Thule.
I forget, I must have had at least I must have had two or three thousand people.
Three or four thousand.
Three or four thousand.
Scattered very thin.
But now, of course, that doesn't include the
huge bases that gave me support.
Directly under my command.
This is your first command?
First large command, yes.
First command at division level.
I've had squadrons.
Oh yeah, but I mean first command at division level.
This is quite a boost for your career.
Oh yeah, and I liked, as a matter of fact, I remember, well, I eventually, before I took that, from the Air Defense
section I had under deputy for operations in the act.
I eventually became the deputy for operations under General Myers when they changed commanders.
Then from the deputy for operations, I went over and took the 64th Air Division.
I changed from a staff job in operations to a full command job.
So there again, I did the planning.
I was very fortunate.
I did the planning.
I implemented the plans.
Then I took over command of the units for me.
moved them into the installation that commanded them.
So it was a complete cycle, which I enjoyed very much.
Besides the technical aspects, did you have any other challenges?
I can't remember any unusual ones, except maybe at Thule.
We had some more outcome at the time.
At Thule, you have 180 days of so-called
182 days, if you will, of sunlight, 182 days of night.
Generally speaking, for complete darkness, total darkness 24 hours a day, I think I remember it's about 81 days during the wintertime when the sun never gets above the horizon.
And of course you can say the opposite thing during the middle of the summer when the sun just rotates right around the top of you, just stays above your head.
In the wintertime, and I remember I used to feel this when I'd go up on a staff visit to the field.
You know, my unit's up in Tulane State for about three or four days.
You know, get up, it's dark.
Go to bed, it's dark.
Get up, it's dark.
Go to bed, it's dark.
Dark all the time.
And psychologically, I could feel the effect.
Now, imagine a guy being assigned a term for six months.
The usual assignment was six months?
Yeah, we had to shorten it to six months because it was for our reasons.
in the wintertime particularly, and we'd give them leave, bring them back down, you know.

We had hospital cases in the hospital at St. John Newfoundland headquarters right there at NEAC, where they were hospital cases of psychological shock and so forth from the total darkness season up until then.
No kidding.
But these were usually the younger, less experienced people.
And how did you combat that?
How did you combat these morale wars?
Bringing them out of the area and then getting them, you know, mental therapy there at the hospital.
Generally, we would never send those types back.
And would you give, well, what about your regular people that were up there for six months and the officers were up there too for six months only?
The what?
Officers and men?
Oh, sure.
Okay.
The commanders went to the base?
And the...
Well, the fighter crews eventually had up there for three aircraft, alert crews, you know, standing alert.
We'd bring them back during that 81 days.
We had tried to arrange, you know, we had the Air Transport Command was particular.
Well, you know, we had to.
The only way to get supplies up there was by air.
It was landlocked, you know, ice.
You couldn't get ships up there.
We planned the massive shipments in the summertime, all laid on by the military...
Well, the ocean, the Navy.
And if you didn't get that up there during that shipping season, then you knew you were going to have to carry it up by air later on.
And you know, you can't carry some of the heavy cargo.
You just can't afford to carry it all in the air.
So we had a lot of air transportation in the wintertime during that darkness period.
And we would bring the people back down south.
the Pepperell Air Force Base.
Some of them we even sent down maybe to back to the States for a week or two, vacation and leave, you know.
It didn't take up much time.
A lot of the people, the majority I'd say, didn't bother.
It's only a few of the cases.
All of us talked about it and knew it, but there were more mature people, I think,
Did you have movies for them, entertainment?
Oh, yeah.
Gymnasium.
Beautiful gymnasium you ever saw.
Even way up there.
Four basketball courts on the floor.
Oh, yeah.
Movies.
Indoor tennis.
Indoor swimming pools.
How did you ever maintain a swimming pool up there?
Well, it's built above the ground and inside where you...
It's heated.
It's heated.
You know, you keep your potatoes in and heat them.
You don't let them get outside and frozen for the mess.
Everything, you keep things heated.
How cold was it during the winter?
The coldest I ever was was BW-8, an air base that was on the western side of Greenland versus BW-1, the extreme southern tip of Greenland.
That was a route up to the base.
But I remember the coldest
Today I think I remember it was BWA and I think it was 48 degrees below zero.
We had to put the airplane in the hangar immediately upon landing and close the hangar doors because of freezing up the hydraulic system and keep the airplane warm.
There's a lot of funny stories that go on that I could tell you about, but they're unprintable about.
For instance, the boys that go to the outdoor latrines.
When it gets below 40 degrees, operations cease.
Operations cease.
I mean below 40 degrees below zero.
We had a hardy soul, as a side story, called Glowtarts Charlie.
He was building a weather station over here on the eastern coast of Northeastern extreme tip of Greenland.
We dropped a tractor to him, an air portable tractor out of the back end of a C119.

I think in the open season, shipping season, he came up off the eastern coast of Greenland and he had a, he started out from a weather shack which was a Danish weather station in the southern area, but he, we wanted this weather station further up north and he was going to start out from there.
The reason we call him Bloat Tarts Charlie is that the only way he could get his tractor started was diesel.
He had to use Bloat Tarts to get the manifold system and he just had fuel lines and all to get the tractor started.
And he wouldn't go any place without a Bloat Tart.
Did you like having your first divisional command?
Yeah, I liked it very much.
Did you enjoy the command part of it, the administration?
I loved it.
They had good people under me and it was basically a National Guard outfit that they had deployed up from the state of New York.
No kidding.
And in fact, I took it over as one of the few National Guard units that was taken over by the Air Force and inducted and sent overseas, if you will, as a unit.
Usually they broke them up and filled regular units with them.
At first, I had a few morale problems.
They objected to an outsider coming in and taking over their unit.
They forgot that they were in the Air Force.
They still thought it was a nice guard unit from the ER.
But it didn't take long to overcome that.
How did you overcome it?
Talking to them.
I never did really have any problems with the command.
I enjoyed it.
I like to handle people.
Okay.
Let's go to your next question.
your next assignment from June 54th to October 56th.
Okay.
To Colorado.
Yeah, Colorado.
Okay, Colorado.
Well, here again is Conrad.
Con-ed.
Yeah.
Air Defense Command.
Yeah.
Well, here again, and here you can see what was a logical pattern that sometimes you don't see in the armed forces.
Here was a logical pattern of a man calling it career, air defense.

It was logical that I would leave that part of the North American continent where I had implemented plans and supervised the construction of air defense units, both fighters and ground control equipment.
then go back to the very headquarters of what was to be the headquarters of the entire North American air defense system, which that was a part of.
The 64th Air Division was a part of it.
And continue in the planning and operations
for coordination of the entire nationwide, continent-wide air defense system.
So I went back, I went to Colorado and was assigned to headquarters in their defense system.
Now, Continental Air Defense System consisted of, it was a joint command.
It consisted of the United States Army, the United States Air Force Air Defense Command, and

We even got the Navy included with about 13 people and a Navy admiral trying to incorporate the United States Navy into this system from the standpoint of air defense and to be more specific on the secret extensions of early warning ships at sea, maybe 150 to 200 miles out to sea.
And even the Navy early warning aircraft
airborne radars off the sea approaches to the, both through the Atlantic and Pacific approaches to the United States.
In other words, practically 270 degrees of protection for the northeast and west, and leaving really the only way bombers could come in the United States was to come across Mexico.
And still, you know, this took a lot of planning, joint-wise.
And ultimately, of course, to bring in

the RCJF and their joint command of the Royal Canadian Army, or 90 units, anti-aircraft missile, as a combined command, namely NORAD, North American Air Defense System, and some people called it North American Air Defense Command, but NORAD, North American Air Defense.
If I remember correctly, my first job there was, I think it was in plans again.
Operation.
Operation plans.
DCSC ops, yes.
Oh, that's right, yes.
That's right, yes.
I was made assistant DCSO under General Berkowitz.
Mm-hmm.
And exactly what was your function there?
What was your duty there?
I was the assistant.
What does DCS stand for?
Deputy Chief of Staff for Operations.
Oh, okay, so you were the deputy chief for operations, okay.
You'll notice throughout my career I was either operations, which really is a key staff man for conducting, directing the operations of a unit, or I was a commander.
I can't recall ever having a primary job as personnel or material in any of my military service.
I was very smart.
But that's why I did the assistance for operations.
In other words, whenever General Berkley was gone, I was DCSO of the command.
We had two hats, Air Defense Command and Continental Air Defense Command, the Joint Command.
For instance, our boss, the commander, 1st General Kidlaw, he was the commander of the Air Defense Command and reported to the Chief of Staff of the Air Force.
With his joint head on, he was the Joint Commander of the Continental Air Defense Command and reported to the Joint Chief of Staff.
Eventually, when NORAD came in, he was the Combined Commander and was Commander of the North American Air Defense System and reported not only to
the Joint Chiefs of Staff of the United States, but also, to a certain extent, to what was tantamount to the Joint Chiefs of Staff of Canada.
One didn't know right from the other.
See, General Chisdall left, must have been around 58, let me see my, must have been around 58 or 50.
Chitlow was the first commander.
Had to be in the late, late 50s.
No, it was early.
Yeah, late 50s.
I'm not sure about here, but the late 50s.
I'm not sure about here.
Now, what were your challenges here?
What were my challenges?
Yeah.
Just getting the job done.
It was a massive white spread.
Oh, and incidentally, the plan would ultimately break in Alaska.
See, the Alaskan Air Command as a part of the complete North American .
And they had to be integrated in as an extension.
That was planning.
And we eventually called them a, if you will, a direction center for Northwest or Alaskan with the Alaskan Air Defense.
And what kind of air defense did you put in Canada?
Similar to the air defense in the United States.
I mean in Alaska.
Similar to that in the United States, the radars and fighters.
Why did you wait until after Canada, after you did this with Canada?
We didn't wait, I just forgot to tell you about it.
Oh, okay.
We visualized it initially.
Okay, so this is being done back in the 1940s.
Well, planning in the 40s and actually implementing in the 50s.
When I took over the 25th Air Division in Tacoma, McCord Air Force Base, northwestern part of the United States, I had liaison lines to the Vancouver area across the border.
Actually, I commanded operationally.
the Royal Canadian Air Force jet fighters at Vancouver and four radar sites in southwestern Canada.
And I had direct communications with the air defense headquarters in Alaska because, see, I was more adjacent to them.
I had to have early warning pass with me.
I remember scrambling aircraft from, I'm talking too much,
I remember scramming aircraft from my base in Payne Air Force Base just north of Seattle and intercepting a SAC bomber 250 miles north of the Canadian border.
Why?
Catching them that far out.
Why?
Was this a maneuver?
Oh, no.
It was an exercise.
Oh, it was an exercise.
And boy, I loved that.
As a matter of fact, I was proud of it.
I had the long, the old F-89 type, what was called a wagon wheel type, long-range interceptors.
Incidentally, the first one had the atomic air defense weapon on it, air defense missile.
It was called GD, G-D-N-I.
What year was that?
That was in...
That was when I was still at Dorian Headquarters in 56, 55.
We had, we took the air defense genie missile and had it mounted on, we had nuclear air-to-air missile active air defense in the United States in 56, 57.
Nuclear air-to-air?
Still have it.
I didn't realize that.
That must be an awful small warhead.
It is.
Well, that'd do some destruction.
Shooting a nuclear missile at another airplane.
Why would you even need it?
Why would it be necessary?
Positive.
Well, close misses sometimes with a regular missile may not get them.
And this was big enough to get two or three.
Also, you know, the blinding flash that blinded the remaining crew that were in formation.
We're convinced the rest of it doesn't sink.
What about the range on this?
Oh, it got way out in front of us.
That was one of the designs.
Well, you break off two.
We had to have a design special maneuver.
And actually, we tried out at...

out in the Luke Air Force Base out in the desert with, of course, a regular missile with no warhead in it to actually practice the maneuver and determine how best to do it to be sure that the pilot could get away from the missile in time not to be blown up with it.
And, of course, the base maneuver turned immediately and banked away and down.

pick up the fade and get away, and with it back to it, we still had visual blinders that we'd pull down the cockpit, and also on a pilot's visor that he would take the caution to keep from being blinded by the flash.
Of course, he took the flash, what little was, right at the bottom of the airplane, so it turned out a bit.
It was feasible.
About what size of...
bomb would be in one of these missiles, about how many megatons?
Oh, it's very small, a few kilotons.
Yeah, I don't mean megatons.
Kilotons.
But that's the size of the bomb that we dropped on the machine?
No, smaller than that.
This is what you call a tactical type nuke, a tactical nuke, if you will.
Have we ever, to your knowledge, have we ever fired one of these missiles and exploded the warhead on a drone or anything?
Oh, yeah, in lab tests over the moving ground out in Indian Springs where they test all the missiles.
We fired one from an airplane.
and shot down another drone, or shot down a drone, or another?
I didn't do a drone.
I mean, you know.
I don't remember.
Oh, well, it was, there was no doubt about that we could do that.
It was just a matter of firing it, it'd explode, and the pilot could break away from it.
This had been done.
Tested, actually.
Did it destroy the target?
There was no target for it to destroy.
It was just fired up in space.
Oh.
We didn't worry about, you know, getting close enough to destroy the target.
And what was the impact on the pilot?
None.

And as a matter of fact, during that test, three of our staff officers who made your good tank contacts, who were very instrumental in following this program and pushing it from its very initial state to its final completion over a period of two or three years, they were so dedicated to it that they volunteered to stand on the ground
below where that thing was going to be busted that I think it's, I forget how high it was, 15, 20,000 feet.
And they did, they were on the ground below.
And of course they had to cause it with eyeglasses and all that.
The main thing is blindness.
It definitely felt the explosion.
Do you remember what year this was?
All I know it was around the mid-50s.
It was while I was still at .
Now, they were doing a lot of atomic experiments in the mid-1950s and the early 1950s, above ground experiments that we continue to tell of the mid-1960s when we signed a non-proliferation treaty.
And recently, of course, there have been some army men, not officers necessarily, but men who have charged
the United States government with using them as guinea pigs and standing them up in front of atomic blasts.
I even saw this on 60 Minutes.
60 Minutes, remember that program on 60 Minutes?
In which a number of troops were... Yeah, I didn't see it on 60 Minutes, but I know what you're talking about.
They actually had some...
Well, they said that maybe they got some radiation and then they had a higher rate of cancer.
What was your opinion on that one?
Dismissive of your mind.
I actually met a friend when I went to work for TI, Texas Institute.
I met one of my bosses, Nick Davis, an engineer.
He's now a vice president of TI.
He, at that time, was a Marine Corps buck private.
Well, he was a private.
And he was one time in a test in the trenches with his buddies, the Marine Corps boys in the ground, in one of those tests for the purpose of, you know, seeing what effects it would have on them.
Of course, they were far away, safe enough.
He remembers it and didn't bother him.
And he certainly hadn't been suing the governor for any radiation.
Okay.
Now let's go back to your assignment here.
Your assignment changed from CONAD to ADC.
Is that the Air Defense Command?
What year was it?
This is 1956, October of 1956.
Oh, yes, I can explain that.
Now, that's when this is... October 56 to September 57.
Now, that's in 1956 is the day that CONAD was organized as a separate definite joint command, eventually with the idea of making it NORAD.
So we had to separate ADCL.
And we brought in an actual specifically assigned staff with just joint hats on, part of Army, part of Air Force.
Mm-hmm.
And I wasn't part of NORAD.
I was just strictly the Air Force component.
So they just changed, really, on paper, my position as part of the Air Defense Command, which was really the Air Force component of CONAD.
Oh, OK.
It's more or less a paper.
OK, so you were basically doing the same assignment, though, because you were the deputy chief of staff.
I didn't change my desk.
Oh, OK.
It's paper.
OK, so you stayed the same.
Basic job from June 1954 to September 1957.
That's right, exactly.
In effect, I had two jobs, you might say.
Did you like that job?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
It was very interesting.
And again, I was in the mainstream of everything.
And incidentally, it was during that time that, no, no, forget what I said.
Well, I was wondering about, you know, during the mid-1950s, throughout the internment,
1950s, the Strategic Air Command was popularized and almost glamorized.
There were a number of movies about this.
